'''華盛頓地鐵綠線''' ({{lang-en|Washington Metro Green Line}})，是[[華盛頓地鐵|華盛頓地鐵]]系統的高運量[[城市軌道交通系統|大眾捷運路線]]；在美國[[華盛頓特區|華盛頓特區]]以及[[喬治王子縣|喬治王子縣]][[馬里蘭州|馬里蘭州]]內，從{{link-en|分支大道站|Branch Avenue station}}到[[绿带站|绿带站]]共設有21座[[捷運車站|捷運車站]]，亦為華盛頓初期地鐵計劃中最新完成的一條線，也是穿過華盛頓特區的三條南北路線之一；此外，本路線在[[朗方廣場站|朗方廣場站]]到[[绿带站|绿带站]]區間與[[華盛頓地鐵黃線|黃線]]共用。

== 規劃 ==
{{transh}}
Planning for Metro began with the Mass Transportation Survey in 1955, which attempted to forecast both freeway and mass transit systems sufficient to meet the needs of the region projected for 1980.<ref>Schrag at p. 33-38.</ref> In 1959, the study's final report included two rapid transit lines which anticipated subways in downtown Washington.<ref>Schrag at p. 39.</ref> Because the plan called for extensive freeway construction within the District of Columbia, alarmed residents lobbied for legislation which both created a new transportation agency and blocked freeway construction.<ref>Schrag at p. 42.</ref> The agency, the National Capital Transportation Administration, issued a 1962 ''Transportation in the National Capital Region'' report, which did not include the route that became the Green Line.<ref>Schrag at p. 55.</ref>  A central route under 7th Street in downtown was only added in 1967 primarily to serve the "inner city."<ref>Schrag at p. 112.</ref>

In March 1968, the [[Washington_Metropolitan_Area_Transit_Authority|Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) board approved its {{convert|98|mi|km|adj=on}} Adopted Regional System (ARS) which included the Green Line from Branch Avenue to Greenbelt. It also foresaw possible future extensions to [[Laurel,_Maryland|Laurel, Maryland]] and [[Brandywine,_Maryland|Brandywine, Maryland]].<ref>Schrag at p. 117.</ref>
{{transf}}
=== 早期定案 ===
{{transh}}
Plans for rapid transit prior to the creation of WMATA in February 1967 focused on the needs of commuters while neglecting some of the District's less affluent neighborhoods.<ref name="Schrag at p. 106">Schrag at p. 106.</ref> However, by late 1966, some plans started to include a line along 7th Street in the District of Columbia.<ref name="Schrag at p. 106"/> The new line was included in WMATA's master plan for its proposed then-101-mile system in 1968.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart">{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=March 18, 1982 |title=Metro to Halt Start of Leg To Rosecroft |newspaper=Washington Post }}</ref> At that time, a Green Line was planned to pass through some of the area's poorest and most transit-dependent neighborhoods and provide them with subway service.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> Riots following the death of [[Martin_Luther_King_Jr.|Martin Luther King]] in 1968 destroyed much of the commercial district around 14th and U Streets, and planners hoped that adding a subway stop in that area would stimulate redevelopment.<ref>Schrag at p. 211-12.</ref> The original 1969 plan called for a line under 13th Street NW with just two stations. However, in 1970, the District of Columbia Council agreed to pay an additional $3 million to add a third station and reroute the Green Line under U Street, and 14th Street NW.<ref name="Schrag at p. 213">Schrag at p. 213.</ref> The southern part of the Green Line was originally planned to pass over the [[11th_Street_Bridges|11th Street Bridges]] to the intersection of Good Hope Road SE and Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue SE,<ref name="DecadesFrustrating">{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=December 27, 1991 |title=Decades of Frustrating Debate Kept Green Line Sidetracked |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> follow Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue SE to [[Suitland_Parkway|Suitland Parkway]], down Suitland Parkway to Branch Avenue SE, and down Branch Avenue to a terminus at the intersection of Branch Avenue and the [[Interstate_495_(Capital_Beltway)|Capital Beltway]].<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /><ref name="Feaver">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas |date=October 18, 1977 |title=Metro Choices Detailed |newspaper=Washington Post }}</ref><ref name="Vesey">{{cite news |last=Vesey |first=Tom |date=June 23, 1982 |title=Green Line War Heats Up Again |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Public hearings on whether to build a Green Line and the route it should take were completed in 1973,<ref name="WilliamsThreaten" /> and portions of the line were originally scheduled to open in 1976.<ref name="Branching">{{cite news |last=Vesey |first=Tom |date=December 17, 1983 |title=Metrorail, Now 7, Branching Out |newspaper=[[The_New_York_Times|New York Times]]}}</ref> However, many delays in construction led to the first Green Line stations not opening until 1991.<ref name="Schrag at p. 213" />

The downtown segment of the line was originally projected to open in September 1977.<ref name="s214">Schrag at p. 214.</ref> Obtaining approval of the District of Columbia and Prince George's County of the exact alignment of the Green Line north of U Street delayed construction. Originally, the ARS called for the line to be placed in the median strip of the planned [[North_Central_Freeway_(Washington,_D.C.)|North Central Freeway]],<ref name="s214" /> but after that road was cancelled, the route of the replacement subway tunnel became controversial, resulting in years of expensive delays.<ref>Schrag at p. 214-16.</ref>

The tunnel between the {{wmata|Gallery Place}} and {{wmata|Waterfront}} stations, including the junction with the future [[Yellow_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Yellow Line]], was built at the same time as the other Metro tunnels in downtown Washington in the early 1970s. During construction under 7th Street and U Street, where the [[Tunnel#Cut-and-cover|cut-and-cover]] technique was used, street traffic and pedestrian access on those streets was difficult.<ref>Schrag at p. 217.</ref> That led to the closure of the traditional retail businesses along the route.{{cn|date=April 2019}}

The southern section of the line was not spared from issues, however. The site of Anacostia station, set for the intersection of Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue SE and Good Hope Road SE, led to concerns that the station would destroy historic Old Anacostia, and after pressure from the federal government, Metro moved the site of the station to Howard Road SE.<ref name="DecadesFrustrating" />

By late 1977, Metro had pushed the opening of the Green Line to June 1983.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schedule Calls for Metro Extensions Into Maryland in November |newspaper=Washington Post |date=June 24, 1977}}</ref> Increasing construction costs and financing problems (caused primarily by the inability of local governments to contribute their share of Metro's funding) led WMATA to consider shifting the Green Line to a more southerly route, along Wheeler Road SE, to terminate near [[Rosecroft_Raceway|Rosecroft Raceway]].<ref name="Feaver" /> Another alternative would have built two Green Lines, one following Wheeler Road SE with a terminus at [[Southern_Avenue_(Washington,_D.C.)|Southern Avenue]] and the other following Suitland Parkway to Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue SE, proceeding northerly along Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue SE to Good Hope Road SE, and terminating at Good Hope Road SE and {{wmata|Minnesota Avenue}} SE (then called "Anacostia Station").<ref name="Feaver" />

In October 1977, WMATA's Board of Directors refused to declare construction of the Green Line a "high priority" (favoring extension of the [[Red_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Red Line]] to {{wmata|Glenmont}}) although it instructed Metro staff to work on plans to fund the line and to determine its route.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=October 28, 1977 |title=Metro Board Endorses Cheaper Glenmont Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Although the [[United_States_Department_of_Transportation|United States Department of Transportation]] approved the Glenmont extension, federal officials were unhappy that Metro had yet to construct the Green Line into [[Anacostia,_Washington,_D.C.|Anacostia]].<ref name="ReferenceA" />

In January 1978, a WMATA regional task force approved a Green Line route in Anacostia that followed Martin Luther King, Jr., Avenue and then Wheeler Road down to the Beltway, with a new station added near [[St._Elizabeths_Hospital|St. Elizabeths Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=January 19, 1978 |title=Anacostia Metro Shift, Greenbelt Route Rejection Backed |newspaper=Washington Post }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=May 4, 1978 |title=100-Mile Metro Backed |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Nonetheless, the Prince George's County government successfully demanded in May 1978 for WMATA to choose the Suitland Parkway to Rosecroft route instead.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=April 26, 1978 |title=P.G. Council Votes for 2 Metro Routes |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=May 10, 1978 |title=Prince George's County Council Chooses Rosecroft Metro Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> In August 1978, WMATA's Board of Directors recommended to the federal government and its partner state and local governments for the entire {{convert|100|mi|km|adj=on}}-long Metrorail system to be fully built, a proposal that included immediate construction of the {{wmata|Archives}}, {{wmata|Waterfront}}, {{wmata|Navy Yard–Ballpark}}, and {{wmata|Anacostia}} stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=August 5, 1978 |title=Cost of Subway Is Now Estimated At $6.6 Billion |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA announced in November 1978 that it had secured funding to build the Green Line from Gallery Place to Waterfront and that construction was nearly complete on that portion of the line, but that funding did not exist to push the line from Waterfront to Anacostia.<ref name="FeaverCompletion">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=November 19, 1978 |title=Metro Completion Expected in 10 Years |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Nonetheless, Metro reiterated that it intended to complete the extension by late 1983.<ref name="FeaverCompletion" />

Two additional realignments occurred at the north end of the Green Line but with less acrimony. North of {{wmata|Fort Totten}}, the line was to have surfaced in the median of the planned North Central Freeway, [[Interstate_95_in_Maryland|I-95]], and to have proceeded to a point just west of {{wmata|Prince George's Plaza}}, with an intermediate station at [[Chillum,_Maryland|Chillum]]. I-95 and Metro would have run through the [[Anacostia_River|Northwest Branch]] Stream Valley Park, but the cancellation of I-95 through the District and out to the [[Interstate_495_(Capital_Beltway)|Beltway]] in 1974 meant that it was no longer necessary or appropriate to condemn an I-95-sized swath of parkland just for Metro. WMATA eventually selected a new route that skirted most of the park, and it was federally approved by the mid-1980s. The planned Chillum station was relocated and named {{wmata|West Hyattsville}}. The other alignment dispute occurred in the [[Petworth,_Washington,_D.C.|Petworth]] section of Washington and involved whether the tunnel would go under or skirt [[Rock_Creek_Cemetery|Rock Creek Cemetery]] and how to go through its soft-[[soil|soil]] burial ground (i) and the least disruptive way under New Hampshire Avenue from {{wmata|Georgia Avenue–Petworth}} to {{wmata|Columbia Heights}}. The tunnels eventually skirted the cemetery by using the [[New_Austrian_tunnelling_method|New Austrian tunnelling method]] and stacked under New Hampshire Avenue.
{{transf}}
===法律和資金之爭===
[[File:Naylor_Road_Station.jpg|thumb]][[馬里蘭州|馬里蘭州]]的{{link-en|內勒路站|Naylor Road station}}]]
{{transh}}
In December 1978, Metro announced that the new completion date of the Green Line past the Anacostia station to Rosecroft Raceway would be 1987, a year later than anticipated.<ref name="EisenChanges">{{cite news |last=Eisen |first=Jack |date=November 19, 1978 |title=Metro Votes Changes In Schedules and Plans |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Metro also announced that cost considerations had forced it to abandon the high-vault ceiling design for all unbuilt stations (except Navy Yard), and that a less-costly design would be used at all unbuilt Green Line stations.<ref name="EisenChanges" /> By July 1979, despite the release of billions of dollars in construction funds by the U.S. Department of Transportation, Metro had pushed back the construction of the Anacostia station to mid-1985 and the completion of the Branch Avenue extension to late 1986.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=July 12, 1979 |title=U.S. Will Release Millions in Metro Building Funds |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> But construction schedules continued to slip: despite reaffirming its construction schedules in December 1979,<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dates Set for Subway Line Openings |newspaper=Washington Post |date=December 2, 1979}}</ref> Metro announced in January 1980 that completion of the Green Line terminus in Prince George's County would be pushed back six more months to 1987.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/128071012.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Jan+26%2C+1980&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post++%281974-Current+file%29&edition=&startpage=A12&desc=.+.+.+And+Fast+Tracks+for+It |title=...And Fast Tracks for It |newspaper=Washington Post |date=January 26, 1980 |page=A12 }}</ref>

Even as Metro officially designated Rosecroft Raceway as the Green Line's southern terminus,<ref name="FeaverResolved">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=March 14, 1980 |title=Anacostia, P.G. Metro Issues Finally Resolved |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> more than half of Prince George's County's representatives in the Maryland state legislature asked [[Governor_of_Maryland|Governor]] [[Harry_Hughes|Harry Hughes]] to review the proposed route after allegations of improper political pressure regarding the 1978 route decision surfaced.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shapiro |first=Margaret |date=February 27, 1980 |title=Group Seeks to Delay Rosecroft Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Metro officials proceeded anyway in March 1984 with Green Line design and planning, and moved the line's completion date up to late 1986.<ref name="FeaverResolved" />
{{transf}}
====1980年危機====
{{transh}}
Funding troubles delayed construction even further. In March 1980, Maryland officials worried that high inflation would leave Metro without enough funds to complete the Green Line, forcing Maryland to bear these construction costs alone.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=March 28, 1980 |title=Inflation, Funding Uncertainty May Slow Metro Construction |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> These fears were confirmed in part in September 1980 when Metro announced that inflation had created a $16 million shortfall in its $271 million budget.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=September 19, 1980 |title=Fiscal Woes Mounting For Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> By now, Anacostia residents were increasingly angry at the repeated delays in building the Green Line. In September 1980, D.C. City Council member Jerry A. Moore, Jr. delivered a petition containing 1,000 signatures from Anacostia residents demanding that construction on the Green Line be sped up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=September 26, 1980 |title=10-Cent Fare Rise Proposed to Cut Metro's Deficit |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

In October 1980, ''[[The_Washington_Post|The Washington Post]]'' ran a major article asking "What Ever Happened to the Green Line?" in which the newspaper concluded: "The 18.86-mile Green Line, which some argue should have been the first built because it would serve the most disadvantaged sections of the Washington area, is last on the construction list and threatened with extinction."<ref name="Whatever">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=October 14, 1980 |title=What Ever Happened to the Green Line? |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The article confirmed that funds were in place and contracts signed to complete the Green Line to the proposed Anacostia station at Howard Road SE and Martin Luther King, Jr. Avenue SE, but that repeated local opposition in Maryland to the line's actual location had forced planners to delay final siting of the line inside the District of Columbia.<ref name="Whatever" /> Additionally, Maryland businessmen argued that the switch of the terminus from Branch Avenue to Rosecroft Raceway had economically harmed them, and they filed a suit in the [[United_States_District_Court_for_the_District_of_Maryland|United States District Court for the District of Maryland]] demanding a halt to construction of the Green Line until the line's route could be again reconsidered.<ref name="Whatever" />

The District of Columbia government responded by threatening to veto any further Metro subway construction unless construction of the Green Line was made Metro's highest priority.<ref name="FeaverThreat">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=December 12, 1980 |title=D.C. Threatens to Halt Subway Construction Over Green Line Plan |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Twenty-four hours of intense discussions later, Metro agreed to the District government's wishes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=December 13, 1980 |title=Metro Board Agrees to Make Green Line a Top Priority |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Construction began on the Waterfront station, which was largely complete by January 1981.<ref name="DigTunnel">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=March 31, 1985 |title=Metro Ready To Dig Tunnel To Anacostia |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Once complete, the station was used for storage.<ref name="MetroMovestoAnacostia"/> By December 1980, Metro was still predicting that the Green Line to Anacostia would open in July 1986,<ref name="FeaverThreat" /> but in January 1981, Metro admitted that the line would not open until at least 1990 because of funding constraints.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=January 30, 1981 |title=Status of Future Metro Openings |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Two months later, Metro estimated the cost of building the Green Line from U Street NW to Anacostia at $175 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=March 6, 1981 |title=Metro Says $502 Million Will Be Wasted If Subway System Is Held to 62 Miles |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
====1981年====
{{transH}}
Controversies regarding the siting of the Green Line continued. In May 1980, a group of business owners near the former proposed terminus at Branch Avenue and Auth Road near [[Marlow_Heights,_Maryland|Marlow Heights]] sued Metro on the grounds that the decision to change the course of the Green Line was illegal because it had been undertaken without a public hearing (in violation of Metro's rules).<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /><ref name="FeaverDOTWarns">{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=April 4, 1981 |title=DOT Warns Metro About Rosecroft Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> In February 1981, Judge [[Norman_Park_Ramsey|Norman Park Ramsey]] of the [[United_States_District_Court_for_the_District_of_Maryland|U.S. District for Maryland]] held that Metro did not correctly advertise the hearings at which the change would be discussed.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /><ref name="Vesey" /> Metro appealed the ruling, and Judge Ramsey did not [[Injunction|enjoin]] Metro from proceeding with construction until the appeal was resolved.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> The Prince George's County government, however, reaffirmed in April 1981 its support for the Rosecroft Raceway terminus, and Metro promised to hold a public hearing on the issue in June 1981.<ref name="FeaverDOTWarns" /> Shortly thereafter, the civil rights office of the U.S. Department of Transportation sent a letter to Metro warning that the Rosecroft Raceway route could negatively impact two historically black communities nearby.<ref name="FeaverDOTWarns" /> In May 1981, Metro changed its estimate for the opening of the Green Line to Anacostia to early 1988.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feaver |first=Douglas B. |date=May 29, 1981 |title=Prognosis for Subways Is Later or Shorter |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Prince George's County officials continued to worry that cutbacks in federal funding for mass transit might lead to the cancellation of the four proposed stations in the county ({{wmata|Southern Avenue}}, {{wmata|Naylor Road}}, {{wmata|Suitland}}, and {{wmata|Branch Avenue}}).<ref name="Burgess">{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=July 31, 1981 |title=Pr. George's Holding Up Metro Pact |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Prince George's County officials vetoed in July 1981 any further expenditure of Metro's construction funds unless Metro diverted $100 million from the [[Red_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Red Line]] extension in [[Montgomery_County,_Maryland|Montgomery County]] to {{wmata|Glenmont}} and began the immediate purchase of land and [[Right-of-way_(transportation)|rights-of-way]] in Prince George's County.<ref name="Burgess" /> Metro agreed a month later to the plan, with the provision that $90 million per year would be spent to begin work on the inner-city portion of the Green Line (the Gallery Place, Waterfront, and Navy Yard stations).<ref>{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=August 28, 1981 |title=Metro Board Recommends Starting Construction on All Lines by 1985 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Metro held its long-awaited hearings over the Green Line's route in October 1981, but only in Prince George's County (not the District).<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> A month later, the [[United_States_Court_of_Appeals_for_the_Fourth_Circuit|4th Circuit Court of Appeals]] turned down Metro's appeal.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /><ref name="Vesey" /> Metro subsequently estimated on December 9, 1981, that the Green Line would reach Anacostia in late 1989.<ref name="APNursery">{{cite news |last=Komarow |first=Steven |date=December 10, 1981 |title=Congressional Nursery Threatens Subway Stall |newspaper=[[Associated_Press|Associated Press]]}}</ref>
{{transf}}
====1982年====
{{transh}}
Funding problems delayed construction even further. In February 1982, [[President_of_the_United_States|President]] [[Ronald_Reagan|Ronald Reagan]] proposed cutting Metro construction funds by 21.4% to just $295 million a year.<ref name="WilliamsThreaten">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Juan |date=February 25, 1982 |title=Budgets, Politics Threaten Green Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Planned Green Line construction constituted 40.5% of Metro's construction budget, and the cuts threatened to cancel the entire Green Line.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart"/><ref name="WilliamsThreaten" /> To African American community leaders, the cuts were evidence that Metrorail was meant for suburban white commuters while inner city African Americans were relegated to taking Metrobus.<ref name="WilliamsThreaten" /> Despite the funding troubles, Metro planned to seek contractors in March 1982 for a $60 million contract to tunnel under the Anacostia River, a $60 million contract to build the Anacostia station, and a $100 million contract to build the Navy Yard station.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> However, on March 16, 1982, Judge Ramsey barred Metro from spending any money on the construction of the Rosecroft Raceway route for the southern half of the Green Line.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> The judge held that Metro had decided to shift the Green Line route without properly advertising the public hearings, which the transit system would now be required to hold again, delaying construction of the Green Line and Anacostia station by at least a year.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> Although Metro had advertised the hearings, Judge Ramsey said, the advertisements contained the same wording flaws that had precipitated the Maryland lawsuit.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> Metro subsequently scheduled new hearings for June 1982.<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" />

Metro officials considered shifting construction funds from the southern Green Line to the northern Green Line in order to start construction on that end of the line,<ref name="BurgessHaltStart" /> but the D.C. City Council opposed this shift.<ref>{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=March 26, 1982 |title=Area Governments Ask Metro To Cut Budget $32 Million |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Metro held the court-ordered hearings in June 1982, at which Prince George's residents argued that they had voted for Metro's 1968 bond issue based on the original Green Line route.<ref name="Vesey" /> Metro promised attendees at the hearing that agency staff would study the Green Line route and issue a report recommending a route, after which construction on the Anacostia River tunnel would begin.<ref name="Vesey" /> The site of the tunnel thus became an issue, with some residents arguing for a tunnel from the Navy Yard under Anacostia Park to Martin Luther King, Jr. Avenue SE, while others wanted the tunnel to take a more northerly route alongside the 11th Street Bridges to Good Hope Road SE.<ref name="Vesey" /> In October 1982, Metro estimated that opening of the Green Line to Anacostia would happen in the "late 1980s",<ref>{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=October 5, 1982 |title=Metro Gets $35 Million In U.S. Funds for Land, Parking Lot Construction |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> and in November a Metro staff report recommended construction of the Rosecroft Raceway route.<ref>{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=November 19, 1982 |title=Metro Board Upholds Green Line Route to Rosecroft |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Cuts in federal construction funds for Metro again delayed construction. Metro announced in December 1982 that service on the line would not cross the Anacostia River until late 1989 at the earliest.<ref name="BurgessSchedule">{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=December 23, 1982 |title=New Law Will Again Delay Metro Construction Schedule |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The federal contribution to Metro's construction fund was lowered to $44 million from $95 million for fiscal 1983, and Metro said that it would divert most of that money to dig tunnels from {{wmata|Gallery Place}} to {{wmata|Mount Vernon Square}}.<ref name="BurgessSchedule" /> In February 1983, the Reagan administration proposed cutting Metro's construction budget by $145 million to $230 million, which Metro said would push the opening of the Green Line to 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barker |first=Karlyn |date=February 1, 1983 |title=Budget Could Cost City An Extra $50 Million |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Sandra |date=February 23, 1983 |title=Metro Asks 50% Rise in U.S. Funding |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> On February 11, 1983, Metro, for the first time in its history, formally announced that (absent full construction funding) it could not build the Green Line, the Red Line from {{wmata|Wheaton}} to {{wmata|Glenmont}}, or the Yellow Line from {{wmata|Franconia–Springfield}} to {{wmata|King Street–Old Town}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Burgess |first=John |date=February 11, 1983 |title=Metro Identifies Four Unbuilt Segments Beyond U.S.-Specified 75-Mile Limit |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
====安納科斯蒂亞總站====
{{transh}}
As Metro struggled to secure construction funding for the Green Line and Anacostia station, it also struggled to lift the district court's injunction on Green Line construction. Metro asked the court to allow construction of the Navy Yard, Anacostia, and Congress Heights stations pending a decision on the Green Line route in Prince George's County, but the court refused.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=July 14, 1983 |title=Judge to Consider Metro Bid to Build Green Line in SE. |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Judge Ramsey said that Metro's public hearing process was biased and "inadequate".<ref name="LyntonBars">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=October 5, 1983 |title=Judge Bars Metro From Building Green Line Through Anacostia |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Even as the court refused to let Green Line construction in Anacostia begin, more than 23,000 Anacostia residents signed a public petition demanding that the line be built.<ref name="LyntonBars" /> Metro declined to appeal Judge Ramsey's latest ruling,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=October 21, 1983 |title=Metro Won't Appeal Judge's Ruling That Bars Green Line to Rosecroft |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> and the Prince George's County Council voted to reverse its earlier decision and support the original Green Line route to Branch Avenue.<ref>{{cite news |last=McQueen |first=Michael |date=October 19, 1983 |title=P.G. Council Majority Backs Shift of Subway Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Frustrated by funding constraints and the court injunction, in December 1983 Metro released a proposed "final" system map that showed the Green Line terminating at the Anacostia and Mount Vernon Square stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=December 3, 1983 |title=Metro Plan to Get Funds For Subway Stirs Dispute |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===爭議解決===
[[File:William_Thaddeus_Coleman_-_Cabinet_meeting.jpg|thumb]]
{{transh}}
In 1984, Metro undertook two steps to secure completion of the Green Line. First, the transit agency hired former U.S. Secretary of Transportation [[William_Thaddeus_Coleman_Jr.|William T. Coleman, Jr.]] in December 1983 to oversee negotiations with the various entities involved with the siting of the Green Line route and seek a resolution through the U.S. district court.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=December 22, 1983 |title=Metro Considers Hiring Ex-Transportation Chief To Settle Green Line Feud |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> On February 21, 1984, Prince George's County Executive [[Parris_Glendening|Parris Glendening]] announced that construction of the Green Line in Prince George's must start by September 30, 1984, or he would begin vetoing Metro spending proposals.<ref name="SeekOnTrack">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=February 21, 1984 |title=New Moves Seek to Get Green Line on Track |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> At the same time, Metro and Coleman opened negotiations to build the Green Line from the L'Enfant Plaza Station to Anacostia.<ref name="SeekOnTrack" /><ref name="Accord">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=February 25, 1984 |title=Tentative Accord |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="ClearedGreenLine" /> Advocates of the Rosecroft route, however, warned that they would sue if Metro switched back to the original route.<ref name="SeekOnTrack" />

Just four days later, Metro, D.C. and Prince George's County officials, reached an agreement with advocates of both the Branch Avenue and Rosecroft routes to begin construction from L'Enfant Plaza to Anacostia, pending resolution of the line's final route by December 6, 1984.<ref name="Accord" /><ref name="DeadlineSetDecision">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=February 29, 1984 |title=Deadline Set for Green Line Decision |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The agreement called for construction of the Green Line to Waterfront station in the summer, siting of the tunnel under the Anacostia River by June 28, and the holding of public hearings on the remaining route between July 18 and August 3.<ref name="DeadlineSetDecision" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=March 2, 1984 |title=Metro Board Clears Way for Start on Green Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The U.S. Federal District Court approved the agreement on March 7.<ref name="ClearedGreenLine">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=March 8, 1984 |title=Way Is Cleared For Green Line To Anacostia |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Following the ruling, Metro announced that it would build the Anacostia station on Howard Road between Martin Luther King, Jr. Avenue SE and the Anacostia Freeway, as well as a new Metro station at the Washington Navy Yard, and would open the Green Line by 1990.<ref name="ClearedGreenLine" /> Metro asked and won approval from the court to build the Navy Yard and Anacostia stations and the tunnel in June 1984.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=June 15, 1984 |title=Judge Is Asked To Ease Freeze On Green Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=June 27, 1984 |title=Work May Start This Year |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Metro also began new political efforts to secure funding to complete the transit system. Initially, Reagan administration officials balked at this plan, reiterating that they would not permit Metro to build more than {{convert|76.4|mi|km}} of subway.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=February 2, 1984 |title=Curbs on Metro Expansion To Remain, DOT Chief Says |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> But in June, House and Senate committees passed legislation requiring the Reagan administration to release all funds appropriated for Metro, putting pressure on the administration to rescind its mileage limit.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=May 16, 1984 |title=House Panel Endorses Full Subway Construction |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=June 8, 1984 |title=House Panel Backs Bill To Lift Curb on Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen T. |date=June 29, 1984 |title=Senate Committee Acts to Bar Limits on Metro and National |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===巴士之爭===
{{transh}}
Like all Metrorail stations, Anacostia station was intended to be a major hub for Metrobus service in the area.<ref name="CreatingaBusStorm">{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=September 4, 1991 |title=Bus Riders Creating a Storm |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> However, with the Anacostia neighborhood being the poorest<ref name="CreatingaBusStorm" /> and most transit-dependent area in the District of Columbia, changes to bus routes in the area proved highly controversial. As the opening of the Green Line to Anacostia neared, WMATA proposed halving the number of bus routes traveling between Anacostia and the [[National_Archives_and_Records_Administration#National_Archives_Building|National Archives Building]] downtown. That would force riders to take the more expensive Metrorail and require many riders to walk several blocks to their destination, rather than the "virtually door-to-door service" that they enjoyed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=April 10, 1991 |title=Metro Proposes Cuts in 40 Percent of Its Bus Routes |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> A total of 25 routes were changed, affecting more than 80,000 riders.<ref>Two routes were replaced with new routes; three routes were discontinued without replacement; 12 routes were consolidated with other routes; seven routes were truncated to terminate at the Anacostia station; and one route was expanded. See: {{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=August 27, 1991 |title=Proposal for Buses Raises Hackles in SE |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref name="PackMetroHearings">{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=September 13, 1991 |title=Riders Pack Metro Hearings to Decry Bus Cuts in SE, PG |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref>

Many of the new routes now terminated at the Anacostia station, rather than continuing into downtown Washington.<ref name="Hackles">{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=August 27, 1991 |title=Proposal for Buses Raises Hackles in SE |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=August 2, 1991 |title=Metro Plans More Cuts to Close $10 Million Deficit |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> WMATA officials admitted that fares for most Anacostia residents would rise an average of 50%<ref name="CreatingaBusStorm" /><ref name="Hackles" /> and that Anacostia residents would be forced to pay more and travel farther to access the services (such as doctors) and shopping that most District residents can readily access.<ref name="CreatingaBusStorm" /> To help mediate the impact of the total fare increase on Anacostia residents, WMATA reduced basic bus fares for many routes in the area from $1 to 35 cents.<ref name="Hackles" />
{{transf}}
====抗議和抵制====
{{transh}}
District residents protested the route cuts with a [[picketing|picket line]] in front of WMATA's downtown headquarters in August 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=August 30, 1991 |title=New Line Divides Metro Board |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> Prince George's County residents were also angered by the changes. They argued that Metro had promised more, not less, bus service and complained that they would be forced to use a rail station located in the District of Columbia's most violent and crime-prone neighborhood.<ref name="MetroMovestoAnacostia" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=September 11, 1991 |title=PG Riders of Metro Denounce Bus Cuts |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref name="ServiceWontEnd" /> More than 1,000 people packed "raucous" public hearings for three nights in the District and Prince George's County in early September that denounced Metro and claimed that they were "becoming a victim of transportational apartheid."<ref name="PackMetroHearings" /> Worried about the impact of the cuts as well as a possible bus boycott, [[List_of_mayors_of_Washington,_D.C.|D.C. Mayor]] [[Sharon_Pratt_Kelly|Sharon Pratt Kelly]] announced on September 11, 1991, that she would seek an alternative to the changes proposed by WMATA.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=September 12, 1991 |title=With SE Angry, Dixon Vows to Save Bus Routes |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Suburban commuters were angry that Metro would keep the bus routes open in Anacostia, at an estimated cost of $4 million, when their bus service had been cut when Metrorail stations opened in their areas;<ref name="SuburbsinSnit">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=September 13, 1991 |title=Suburbs in a Snit Over SE Bus Plan |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="BarryJoinsProtest">{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=September 15, 1991 |title=Barry Joins Protest Against Rerouting of SE Buses |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. residents countered that poor [[African_American|African American]] District citizens could not afford the same transit changes and fare increases that wealthy, white suburbanites were asked to absorb.<ref name="SuburbsinSnit" />

[[File:Bus_bays_01_-_Anacostia_Metro_Station_-_2012-06-30.jpg|thumb]]
Calls for a boycott increased in mid-September.<ref name="BarryJoinsProtest" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Purnell |first=John |date=September 15, 1991 |title=Anacostians Talk of Metro Boycott |newspaper=Washington Times |location=[[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]]}}</ref> On September 16, 1991, declaring that the city paid "40 percent of the Metro subsidy, but we're the last to get service," Mayor Dixon threatened to withhold the District's payment to Metro unless the bus changes were rescinded.<ref>McCraw, Vincent. "Dixon Targets Metro's Wallet." ''Washington Times.'' September 17, 1991; Sisler, Peter F. "Dixon to Restore Some SE Bus Cuts." ''Washington Times.'' September 21, 1991.</ref> Metro officials were angered by Dixon's statement and said that District officials had been involved in the bus route planning process for months.<ref>Sisler, Peter F. "Metro: City Was Party to Bus Cuts." ''Washington Times.'' September 18, 1991.</ref> Mayor Dixon proposed on September 20 for Metro to continue to use Anacostia station as a hub but with bus service provided into downtown D.C.<ref name="PlanRetains">Henderson, Nell. "Dixon Plan Retains Trans-Anacostia Buses." ''Washington Post.'' September 21, 1991.</ref> The plan, estimated to cost less than $500,000 a year, would require residents to transfer at Anacostia station but would not raise the total fare to more than $1.<ref name="PlanRetains" /> A month later, Metro's board of directors unanimously agreed to accept Dixon's plan and cancelled all planned route changes in the District of Columbia and Prince George's County.<ref name="ServiceWontEnd">Fehr, Stephen C. "Metro Shifts Stand On SE, P.G. Buses." ''Washington Post.'' October 25, 1991.</ref><ref name="MetroRestores">Keary, Jim. "Metro Restores Most Bus Routes." ''Washington Times.'' October 25, 1991.</ref> The cost of operating the bus routes totaled $2.5 million annually.<ref name="MetroRestores" />  The compromise led residents to call off their boycott of Metrobus.<ref name="RunsSmoothly">Sisler, Peter F. "Anacostia Metro Station Runs Smoothly, Officials Say." ''Washington Times.'' December 31, 1991.</ref>

Prince George's County, meanwhile, had announced that its county-run buses ("[[TheBus_(Prince_George's_County)|The Bus]]") would not run to Anacostia Station, as previously promised, drawing outrage from the D.C. representatives on Metro's board.<ref name="ServiceWontEnd" /> The District of Columbia had spent more than $20 million adding bus bays at the station to accommodate The Bus arrivals.<ref name="ServiceWontEnd" />
{{transf}}
====票價損失====
{{transh}}
Two months after the Anacostia station opened, WMATA said that a study of bus and rail ridership showed that the unaltered bus routes were costing the transit agency $200,000 a month in lost rail fares.<ref name="RidershipFallShort">Fehr, Stephen C. "Metro Sees Ridership Fall Short." ''Washington Post.'' February 28, 1992.</ref> To make up the lost revenue, WMATA said that it would run only two-car trains (the shortest on the system) on the Green Line during slow periods on weekdays and evenings and on Sundays beginning in June 1992.<ref name="RidershipFallShort" /> In November 1992, WMATA reported that ridership at the Anacostia station was (on average) 7,500 riders a day, 700 below estimates.<ref name="RidersMakingSwitch">Henderson, Nell. "SE Metro Riders Making Switch From Bus to Rail." ''Washington Post.'' November 30, 1992.</ref> WMATA admitted that although riders had made the switch from bus to rail, the lower ridership numbers were caused by the [[early_1990s_recession_in_the_United_States|recession]], not because of continuing downtown bus service in the area.<ref name="RidersMakingSwitch" /> Metro said ridership on buses in the neighborhood was down significantly, and the transit agency reduced the number of buses on some routes to avoid having empty buses.<ref name="RidersMakingSwitch" />
{{transf}}
===列車短缺===
{{more|{{link-en|華盛頓地鐵車輛列表|Washington Metro rolling stock}}}}
{{transh}}
WMATA first became aware of a rail car shortage in 1988. Although the transit authority knew that it needed at least 98 new rail cars to provide adequate service to the new stations to be added on the Green Line and other lines by 1993, it did not place an order for the cars.<ref name="PossibleShortage">Henderson, Nell. "Metro Sees Possible Shortage Of Rail Cars Down the Line." ''Washington Post.'' June 13, 1988.</ref> Metrorail also suffered from internal squabbling over rail car design, and rail car production had historically been plagued by poor quality and [[trade_union|labor]] [[strike_action|strikes]]—both of which added to construction delays.<ref name="PossibleShortage" /> By September 1990, more frequent breakdowns in the existing, aging rail car fleet heightened the urgency to buy more cars.<ref name="ClimbAboard">Fehr, Stephen C. "Wheaton, Forest Glen to Climb Aboard Metro." ''Washington Post.'' September 16, 1990.</ref> Officials estimated that the rail car shortage would become critical when the Anacostia station opened.<ref name="ClimbAboard" /><ref name="MetroSettoOpenVanDorn">Keary, Jim. "Metro Set to Open Van Dorn Station." ''Washington Times.'' June 14, 1991.</ref> When the Van Dorn Street station opened in June 1991, Metro was forced to run trains every 12 minutes during rush hour rather than every 8 due to the rail car shortage.<ref name="MetroSettoOpenVanDorn" /><ref>Tousignant, Marylou. "'Metro Groupies' Go Along For 1st Ride From Van Dorn." ''Washington Post.'' June 16, 1991.</ref> Eventually, crowding was addressed when additional cars became available by running 8-car trains.

Metro also encountered significant problems estimating the number of riders who would board the system at the Anacostia and other Green Line stations. In June 1991, WMATA estimated that just over 15,000 riders on average would board at the Waterfront, Navy Yard, and Anacostia stations.<ref>Keary, Jim. "Metro Takes the High-Price Road." ''Washington Times.'' June 25, 1991.</ref> In December 1991, when the Anacostia station opened, Metro had revised that number to 30,700 riders per day (by June 1992).<ref name="AnacostiaAwakens" /><ref name="SpecialPreview">Sisler, Peter F. "150 Anacostians Get Preview of Life With New Metro Station." ''Washington Times.'' December 22, 1991.</ref> Just a week later, Metro dropped that estimate to only 28,000 riders a day (by June 1992).<ref name="AfterFeudsAmidFanfare">Tousignant, Marylou. "After Feuds, Amid Fanfare, Metro Rolls Into Anacostia." ''Washington Post.'' December 29, 1991.</ref>

Even though significant numbers of bus riders in Anacostia had switched to Metrorail by February 1992, WMATA nonetheless began running two- rather than four-car trains on the Green Line on Sundays and during slow periods in order to close a revenue shortfall.<ref name="RidershipFallShort" />

Metro finally ordered new rail cars, but the first of the cars were not due to be delivered until February 2001.<ref name="UnclogGreenLine">Layton, Lyndsey. "Metro Seeks To Unclog Green Line." ''Washington Post.'' January 25, 2001.</ref>

The January 13, 2001 opening of the final five Green Line stations (Congress Heights, Southern Avenue, Naylor Road, Suitland, and Branch Avenue) significantly worsened overcrowding and service problems on the line. The five new stations added almost 20,000 new riders a day, overwhelming station platforms, jamming trains to capacity, and forcing many riders at Anacostia and other stations up the line to wait as train after train passed them, filled.<ref name="RidersFeelCrunch">Layton, Lyndsey. "With 5 New Metro Stations, Green Line Riders Feel Crunch." ''Washington Post.'' January 19, 2001.</ref> Metro had estimated that 18,000 riders a day would board from these stations by June 2001.<ref name="RidersFeelCrunch" /> That estimate was exceeded by 2,000 riders a day on the second day the stations were open.<ref name="RidersFeelCrunch" />

By January 24, the number had risen to more than 30,600 per day, three times as many as originally estimated.<ref name="UnclogGreenLine" /> Angry commuters using the Anacostia, Navy Yard, and Waterfront stations peppered the transit agency with complaints.<ref name="RidersFeelCrunch" /> WMATA claimed that a number of factors contributed to the ridership crunch: the system was experiencing record ridership; two-year-old ridership projections were used; the five stations were opened two months ahead of schedule; the five new stations were opened two months before new rail cars were ready for service; and WMATA offered free parking at the Green Line stations, which drew 12,000 rather than 4,000 riders to the line.<ref name="UnclogGreenLine" />
{{transf}}
==興建與營運==
===1984年===
{{transh}}
Construction of the Green Line south from L'Enfant Plaza began in July 1984 when WMATA issued a call for bids to tunnel under the Anacostia River.<ref name=south>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=July 14, 1984 |title=Excavation Set to Begin On Green Line Tunnel |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The firm of Harrison Western/Franki-Denys (a [[joint_venture|joint venture]]) was awarded the $25.6 million contract, with construction to begin in December 1984.<ref>{{cite news |title=California Company Bid Is Low For Metro's Anacostia Tunnel |date=October 11, 1984 |newspaper=Washington ost}}</ref> WMATA delayed awarding the contract after American [[Apartheid|anti-apartheid]] activists alleged that a [[Belgium|Belgian]] company with a minority financial interest in Franki-Denys did business with the racist white-led government of [[South_Africa|South Africa]], but after the links were discovered to be extremely minor the contract was awarded.<ref name="Choicenear">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=December 13, 1984 |title=Branch Ave. Choice Near for Green Line Route |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="VotestoExpand">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=December 14, 1984 |title=Metro Board Votes to Extend Green Line to Branch Avenue |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>As part of the resolution of the issue, WMATA's Board of Directors agreed to promulgate and implement rules which would tighten the agency's restrictions on awarding contracts to companies doing business in South Africa. Those rules were adopted in May 1985. See: {{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=May 10, 1985 |title=Metro Proposes South Africa Rules |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

The debate over the route for the remainder of the Green Line was finally resolved in December 1984. Residents and D.C. government officials asked WMATA to build stations at [[Congress_Heights|Congress Heights]] and [[Southern_Avenue_(Washington,_D.C.)|Southern Avenue]] in order to promote economic development and provide service to [[St._Elizabeths_Hospital|St. Elizabeths Hospital]] and Greater Southeast Community Hospital.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=July 24, 1984 |title=D.C. Officials Back 2 Metro Stations |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=November 2, 1984 |title=Metro Board to Narrow Choices for Green Line Route Into P.G. |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> In December 1984, WMATA's Board of Directors agreed to return the Green Line to its original route, and build the Congress Heights and Southern Avenue stations.<ref name="Choicenear" /><ref name="VotestoExpand" /> The U.S. district court approved WMATA's decision and dissolved its March 1982 injunction, which had barred construction of the $483 million southern Green Line (now estimated to cost $132 million more than the Rosecroft route).<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=January 3, 1985 |title=Green Line Extension Gets Go-Ahead |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===1985年===
{{transh}}
Funding for Green Line construction fell into place in 1985. Pressured by the previous year's Congressional action, the Reagan administration sought to provide WMATA with $250 million a year for four years to expand the system to {{convert|89.5|mi|km}}, a plan which would not fund construction of the system beyond the proposed Southern Avenue station.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=January 12, 1985 |title=89.5-Mile Subway Seen Near |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=March 20, 1985 |title=U.S. Endorses Metro Plan |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Construction on the line started in 1985. [[Surveying|Survey]] and clearing work for the twin 2,500-foot (762 m) Anacostia River tunnels began in March 1985.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> A 24-foot (7.32 m) long, 19 foot (5.8 m) diameter [[tunnel_boring_machine|tunnel boring machine]] built by the [[Hitachi_Zosen_Corporation|Hitachi Zosen Corporation]] was shipped to the U.S. to drill the tunnel, which required boring techniques "so novel that they have never before been used in the eastern United States."<ref name="DigTunnel" /> The tunnel boring machine ate through "T5" (relatively fine sand mixed with gravel and boulders which occasionally required workers to physically break the boulders apart) and clay formations about {{convert|50|ft|m}} beneath the riverbed.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> The walls of the tunnel were lined with concrete as the machine moved.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> [[Liquid_nitrogen|Liquid nitrogen]] was used to harden the ground where the inbound tunnel reached the northern side of the Anacostia River, to lessen the possibility of cave-ins due to the wet earth.<ref name="GreenLightforGreenLine">{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=April 9, 1987 |title=Green Light for Green Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

[[File:Waterfront-SEU_Station.jpg|thumb]]
The completion date for the two tunnels was estimated at late 1987.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> WMATA engineers also inspected the [[mothball|mothball]]ed Waterfront station<ref name="MetroMovestoAnacostia">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=December 22, 1991 |title=As Metrorail Moves to Anacostia, Questions Remain |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> and found it to be still structurally sound (although water needed to be pumped from the station).<ref name="DigTunnel" /><ref name="AnacostiaAwakens">{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=December 27, 1991 |title=Opening of Anacostia Station Awakens Dormant Area Hopes |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> However, some repairs to the tunnel between L'Enfant Plaza and Waterfront needed to be made.<ref name="GreenLineGrowing">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=September 6, 1991 |title=Green Line Growing Dec. 28 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Construction of the tunnel from Waterfront to Navy Yard was set to begin in September 1985, construction of the Navy Yard station in early 1986, and linkage with the Anacostia River tunnels shortly thereafter.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> The two new Green Line stations were expected to open in 1990.<ref name="DigTunnel" /> In October 1985, WMATA awarded the $24.9 million contract to excavate the tunnel between the Waterfront and Navy Yard stations to Harrison Western Corp.<ref name="Awards2GreenLine">{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=October 25, 1985 |title=Metro Board Awards 2 Green Line Contracts |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA's board awarded a $41.5 million contract for the construction of the Anacostia station to [[Kiewit_Corporation|Kiewit Construction Co.]] in June 1985, and said the station would open in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=June 28, 1985 |title=$50.9 Million Contract Awarded for Shaw Station |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Ground was broken at the site on September 21, 1985.<ref>{{cite news |last=Eisen |first=Jack |date=September 22, 1985 |title=Breaking Ground |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===1986–1988年===
{{transh}}
Funding for construction of the Green Line was threatened again in 1986. WMATA needed $2 billion in construction funds, but Congress was threatening to cut WMATA's funding by up to 26% to $184.5 million a year for four years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=November 4, 1985 |title=Fund Crisis May Derail Metro Plans |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Congress approved $227 million for 1986 in December 1985,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=December 12, 1985 |title=Conferees on Hill Agree To Give Metro $227 Million |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> but the Reagan administration said that it would cut off all funding thereafter.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=December 20, 1985 |title=Official Says White House Is Certain to Ask for Metro Cutoff |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA appealed directly to President Reagan to release $400 million in funds already appropriated,<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=January 10, 1986 |title=Metro Appeals to Reagan to Restore Funding |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> but administration officials said WMATA had more than enough money to complete the Green Line.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=February 6, 1986 |title=Funds Called Available For Metro Green Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=February 7, 1986 |title=Politics Again Stall Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Prince George's County officials threatened to sue Metro as well as block all further construction spending in March 1985 unless WMATA agreed to use its existing funds to build the Green Line into their county.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=March 28, 1986 |title=P.G. Threatens to Block Metrorail Construction |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA officials reacted in June by stretching out construction of the Green Line and Anacostia station to 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=June 15, 1986 |title=Green Line: Red Light |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> After lengthy negotiations (which included state and local guarantees to pay for cost overruns or funding shortfalls, penalties for defaults, and the imposition of two external financial monitors) and heavy pressure from Congress, Reagan administration officials released the $400 million on July 16, 1986.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=July 17, 1986 |title=White House Releases $391.2 Million to Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

[[File:College_Park-U_of_Md_Station.jpg|thumb]]
With the funds released, construction on the Green Line proceeded quickly. In November 1986, WMATA awarded a $36.2 million contract to Mergentime Corp. to build the [[Navy_Yard–Ballpark_station|Navy Yard station]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=November 21, 1986 |title=Metro Awards Contract for Navy Yard Station |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> A month later, WMATA awarded a $19.5 million contract to excavate a tunnel from the Navy Yard Station to the tunnels being built under the Anacostia River.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=December 19, 1986 |title=Fares Stay Same, Subsidies Rise Under Metro Budget Proposal |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> On March 23, 1986, the second of the two {{Convert|2450|ft|m|adj=on}}, concrete-lined tunnels under the Anacostia River was completed.<ref name="MetroMovestoAnacostia" /><ref name="GreenLightforGreenLine" /> With the tunnels finished and other contracts awarded, WMATA announced yet another revised timeline for opening the Green Line in April 1987. The transit agency estimated that the {{wmata|Mount Vernon Square}}, [[Shaw–Howard_University_station|Shaw]], and {{wmata|U Street}} stations would open in late 1990, the Mount Vernon Square to Anacostia link in late 1991, and the {{wmata|Fort Totten}} to {{wmata|Greenbelt}} link by 1994.<ref name="GreenLightforGreenLine" /> In January 1988, WMATA awarded a $179.1 million contract to build the Green Line from Fort Totten to Greenbelt, and a $6.9 million contract to complete the Waterfront station.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Metro Funds Requested |newspaper=Washington Post |date=January 15, 1988 }}</ref> In December 1988, WMATA reaffirmed that the Waterfront, Navy Yard, and Anacostia stations would open in late 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=December 27, 1988 |title=Long-Beleaguered Metro Green Line Creeps to Reality |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===安納科斯蒂亞站南延段===
{{transh}}
Beginning in 1989, WMATA sought funding to extend the Green Line beyond the Anacostia station and to operate the Green Line. Metro asked Congress to authorize $2.16 billion over 10 years to complete the {{convert|103|mi|km|adj=on}} system, as well as appropriate the remaining $193 million from the transit agency's original 1980 authorization to complete the Green Line from Anacostia to {{wmata|Branch Avenue}} and link the Green Line internally between U Street and Fort Totten.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=March 17, 1989 |title=$2 Billion Sought to Finish Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=May 5, 1989 |title=Area Officials on Hill Seek Full Metro Funding |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Although the [[George_H._W._Bush|Bush administration]] opposed the request,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murray |first1=Frank J. |last2=Smith |first2=John E. |date=March 28, 1990 |title=Bush Might Veto Bill to Complete Metrorail System |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Congress provided $2.025 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=March 29, 1990 |title=House Approves $2 Billion to Complete Metrorail System |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="PushesMetroCloser">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=October 26, 1990 |title=Agreement Pushes Metro Closer to the Finish Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Only the stations at {{wmata|Suitland}} and Branch Avenue remained unfunded.<ref name="PushesMetroCloser"/>

By mid-1991, however, falling inflation had reduced WMATA's construction costs so much that the agency said it could build the two final Green Line stations in Prince George's County without asking Congress for additional money.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=June 13, 1991 |title=Metro May Be Finished on Budget, Gunn Says |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA also proposed spending money almost three times faster up-front to accelerate its construction schedule, a move which would be more than compensated for by savings in out-years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=July 12, 1991 |title=Speedup Plan Proposed to Finish Metro By 2001 |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref name="EndofOdyssey">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=July 12, 1991 |title=Metro Eyes End of Odyssey In Year 2001 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Prince George's County officials threatened to block all further Metrorail construction unless they received guarantees that the stations in their county would be built.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=July 26, 1991 |title=PG Puts Its Foot Down on Metro |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> Funding for the remaining seven Green Line stations in the District and Prince George's remained in doubt as of August 1991, with District officials saying that it made sense to build the {{wmata|Georgia Avenue–Petworth}} and {{wmata|Columbia Heights}} stations and Prince George's representatives demanding that the three stations in their county be completed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=August 20, 1991 |title=Local Money Woes May Jeopardize Metro's Last 13 Miles |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> WMATA said that it had so little money it could not fund 16 critical small construction projects, among them security gates at the Navy Yard and Waterfront stations and parts for escalators at the seven new Green Line stations in D.C. and Prince George's County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=November 8, 1991 |title=Metro Asks $20 Million For Projects |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The funding impasse was broken in November 1991 when local and state governments agreed to roughly triple their contribution to Metro's construction costs by 1994 to complete the entire system.<ref name="EdgesTowardPactFinish">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=November 22, 1991 |title=Metro Edges Toward Pact to Finish Rail Line |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

The first WMATA budget which contained funds for operating the Green Line was proposed in December 1989. The budget presumed a December 1, 1990, opening for the Mt. Vernon Square, Shaw–Howard University and U Street–Cardozo stations, and requested funds to test the soon-to-open Green Line from Gallery Place–Chinatown to the Anacostia station.<ref name="MetroBudgetIncludes">{{cite news |last1=Henderson |first1=Nell |last2=Fehr |first2=Stephen C. |date=December 22, 1989 |title=Metro Budget Includes 6 New Stations |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="MetroNotPlanning">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=John E. |date=December 22, 1989 |title=Metro Not Planning Fare Boost for 1990 |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=April 6, 1990 |title=Board Eyes Fare Rise For Metro |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The budget also projected that this section of the line would open in 1991, and that new Metrobus service will be added in Prince George's County to bring commuters to the new station.<ref name="MetroBudgetIncludes" /><ref name="MetroNotPlanning" />
{{transf}}
===延後通車===
====承包商變更====
{{transh}}
The opening of the Green Line was significantly delayed, however, when in May 1990 WMATA fired the contractor building the Shaw–Howard University and U Street–Cardozo stations. Mergentime/[[Tutor_Perini|Perini]] Joint Venture, the contractor working on the stations, had violated its contract with WMATA by reducing the workforce on the project, not meeting project deadlines, and permitting unsafe working conditions to persist.<ref name="PutOffUntil">{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=May 12, 1990 |title=Green Line Opening Put Off Until Spring |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Mergentime/Perini denied the accusations.<ref name="PutOffUntil" /><ref name="NearsCompletion">{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=September 14, 1990 |title=Green Line Nears Completion |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> Although similar problems plagued Mergentime/Perini's work on the Navy Yard station, WMATA did not fire the joint venture company from that project.<ref name="PutOffUntil" /> WMATA said that the problems would delay the Green Line's opening until at least the late spring of 1991.<ref name="PutOffUntil" />

In August 1990, WMATA hired the Perini Corp. as the new contractor, and required the company to finish the job and rebuild the streets in the area, setting a new Green Line dedication of December 1991.<ref name="NearsCompletion" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=August 7, 1990 |title=Green Line Contractor Promises to Rebuild 2 Streets By May |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Federal monitors overseeing WMATA's spending, however, issued a report in August 1990 accusing WMATA of poor financial oversight of the project and blamed the transit agency for the delays and problems Mergentime/Perini confronted.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Nell |date=August 7, 1990 |title=Federal Report Cites Metro in Green Line Delay |url=https://archive.org/details/rupert0000hend_c6v6 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Mergentime/Perini sued WMATA, claiming that it was improperly dismissed from the project.<ref name="NearsCompletion" />
{{transf}}
====其他問題====
{{transh}}
The cost of testing and operating the Green Line left WMATA struggling financially. These costs (along with costs associated with extending and operating the [[Blue_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Blue Line]] to {{wmata|Van Dorn Street}}) forced WMATA to cut 335 jobs as well as supplies, travel, overtime, and temporary employee budgets.<ref name="DrasticCuts">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=December 14, 1990 |title=Metro Set For 'Drastic' Reductions |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Although ridership was projected to rise 3.8% to 260 million trips in the coming year,<ref>{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=January 4, 1991 |title=Metro Wants $1 Fare, A Record 15-Cent Rise |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=January 4, 1991 |title=Metro Set to Raise Base Fare to $1 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> the increased revenue was not expected to cover the costs of operating the new lines and stations.<ref name="DrasticCuts" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=May 17, 1991 |title=Metro Board Imposes 18 Pct. Increase Over Two Years |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Mount Vernon Square, Shaw–Howard University, and U Street–Cardozo stations opened on Saturday, May 11, 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=May 5, 1991 |title=Going Was Tough, but Green Gets Going |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

Construction of the Green Line past Anacostia station was complicated by the discovery of a potential toxic waste site in the path of the subway. In June 1991, WMATA discovered that the District of Columbia had dumped 426,000 tons<ref name="EdgesTowardPactFinish" /> of possibly hazardous [[incinerator_bottom_ash|incinerator bottom ash]] in an unused exposed [[culvert|culvert]] along the subway's potential path near St. Elizabeth's Hospital between 1977 and 1989.<ref name="DumpedAsh">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=June 21, 1991 |title=D.C. Dumped Ash at Site Despite Metro's Plans |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name="Ashes">{{cite news |last=Keary |first=Jim |date=January 4, 1991 |title=Ashes Fill Path of Metro's Expansion |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> The city continued to dump the ash at the site for four years after it learned that WMATA planned to use the site for the Green Line.<ref name="DumpedAsh" /><ref name="Ashes" /> Experts were concerned that the ash dump contained pockets of [[Methane|methane gas]] and soluble acid, which would make the site unusable by Metrorail.<ref name="SeeRed" />

Maryland officials used the discovery to press yet again for realignment of the Green Line and abandonment of the planned stations at Congress Heights and Southern Avenue in favor of construction of the stations at {{wmata|Naylor Road}}, Suitland, and Branch Avenue.<ref name="EndofOdyssey" /><ref name="SeeRed">{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=June 24, 1991 |title=Green Line Plan Makes SE See Red |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> The proposal led to public protests against the Maryland plan in Anacostia, and heated arguments on the WMATA board of directors.<ref name="EndofOdyssey" /><ref name="SeeRed" /> In an initial report in June 1991, WMATA determined that ash posed no environmental risk,<ref name="SeeRed" /> although there were concerns that the level of pollutants would prevent any excavated material from being accepted by landfills in D.C., Maryland, or Virginia.<ref name="DumpedAsh" /> A final environmental report in November 1991 found that the ash was not hazardous, but would need to be removed at a cost of $1 million.<ref name="EdgesTowardPactFinish" />
{{transf}}
===1991年延伸===
[[File:Lake_Artemesia_pier.jpg|thumb]] was created when WMATA mined sand and gravel at this location to build the Green Line.]]
{{transh}}
The Green Line from L'Enfant Plaza to Anacostia opened as scheduled on December 28, 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=December 6, 1991 |title=Metro Yellow, Green Lines To Change Service Sunday |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=December 29, 1991 |title=New Green Line Stations Impress First-Time Riders |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> Ridership expanded rapidly on the Green Line. In the first workweek of the year, more than 8,000 riders a day boarded at the three stations in Southeast D.C. (more than 5,000 of them at Anacostia), exceeding WMATA's estimates,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=January 10, 1992 |title=Two-car Trains Pulling Their Load for Metro |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref> and nearly 10,000 riders were boarding each day at the three stations by the third week of January.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=January 24, 1992 |title=Bus Service, Work Force Cut in Proposed Metro Budget |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sisler |first=Peter F. |date=January 24, 1992 |title=Some in D.C. to Get Free Metro Rides |newspaper=Washington Times}}</ref>

Construction of the Green Line near [[Berwyn_Heights,_Maryland|Berwyn Heights, Maryland]] resulted in the creation of [[Lake_Artemesia|Lake Artemesia]]. In 1976, WMATA removed sand and gravel needed for construction from open space adjacent to the Green Line. In exchange, WMATA paid to develop the area as a lake surrounded by a park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://outdoors.pgparks.com/3244/Lake-Artemesia-Natural-Area |title=Lake Artemesia Natural Area |publisher=Maryland-National Capital Park And Planning Commission |access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>
{{transf}}
===1993年延伸===
{{transh}}
The Green Line stations at [[綠帶站|綠帶站]], [[學院公園-馬里蘭大學站|學院公園-馬里蘭大學站]], [[喬治王子廣場站|喬治王子廣場站]], and [[西海恩茲維爾站|西海恩茲維爾站]] opened in December 1993.<ref>{{cite news |last=Naylor |first=Janet |date=November 23, 1993 |title=Green Line Ready to Roll, to 4 Futuristic Stations |newspaper=Washington Times |location=[[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] }}</ref> Almost two years later, WMATA broke ground on the Suitland, Naylor Road, Southern Avenue, and Congress Heights stations, a $900 million project which would complete the final {{Convert|6.5|mi|km}} of the originally-planned {{Convert|103|mi|km|1|adj=on}} Metrorail system in late 1999.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fehr |first=Stephen C. |date=September 23, 1995 |title=After 25 Years of Building, Metro Nears Finish Line |newspaper=Washington Post |location=[[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bell |first=Rudolph |date=September 24, 1995 |title=Metro Celebrates Breaking Ground For Final Leg in PG |newspaper=Washington Times |location=[[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] }}</ref><ref name="LightatEnd">{{cite news |last=Siew |first=Walden |date=June 5, 1998 |title=Light at the End of the Tunnel |newspaper=Washington Times |location=[[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] }}</ref> The outbound tunnel to Congress Heights was completed in June 1998.<ref name="LightatEnd" /> The Georgia Avenue–Petworth and Columbia Heights stations were completed in September 1999, three months ahead of schedule.<ref>Miller, Bill. "Residents Take Green Line Complaints to Court." ''Washington Post.'' April 18, 1998; Layton, Lyndsey. "Link to the Future." ''Washington Post.'' September 18, 1999; Layton, Lyndsey. "Metro Goes to New Heights." ''Washington Post.'' September 19, 1999.</ref> The Green Line's final five stations opened on January 13, 2001.<ref name="GreenLineFinalFive">Aizenman, Nurith C. "County Sees Green in Metro's Arrival." ''Washington Post.'' January 11, 2001; "Commuters Welcome Opening of Green Line Extension." ''Washington Times.'' January 13, 2001; Layton, Lyndsey. "All Metro Doors Now Open." ''Washington Post.'' January 14, 2001.</ref>
{{transf}}

===近年===
{{transh}}
Service on the Green Line tracks began on May 11, 1991 on three stations between U Street and Gallery Place–Chinatown. Initially, all trains through this section were run as [[Yellow_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Yellow Line]] trains terminating at {{wmata|Huntington}}. The Green Line formally began on December 28, 1991, with three stations south of L'Enfant Plaza to Anacostia. At this time, Yellow Line service north of Mount Vernon Square was discontinued and those stations were served only by the new Green Line. The four-station branch north of Fort Totten to {{wmata|Greenbelt}} opened on December 11, 1993. The two segments were connected on September 18, 1999, with two stations opening, and the last five stations south to Branch Avenue opened on January 13, 2001, completing the original {{convert|101|mi|km|adj=on}} Metrorail system.<ref name="history">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/about/upload/History-090418.pdf |title=Metro History |date=September 4, 2018 |publisher=Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority |access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>

After the branch north of Fort Totten opened, the Green Line Commuter Shortcut began as a six-month experiment on January 27, 1997, allowing passengers to get on a train on the Green Line segment during rush hours and travel as far as {{wmata|Farragut North}} on the Red Line without having to switch trains at Fort Totten; a transfer was needed during off-peak hours. This was accomplished by utilizing a single-track spur (B & E connection<!--explain-->) between the Green and Red Lines near (and bypassing) Fort Totten station. This shortcut was so well-received that it was continued until September 17, 1999, when the mid-city portion of the Green Line was completed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/community_outreach/lunchtalk_online_chats/transcript.cfm?ChatID=184|title=Metro - Community Outreach - Lunchtalk Online Chat|publisher=WMATA|date=March 6, 2009|access-date=March 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227224335/http://wmata.com/community_outreach/lunchtalk_online_chats/transcript.cfm?ChatID=184|archive-date=December 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name="history" />

In 2006, WMATA board member [[Jim_Graham|Jim Graham]] and D.C. Mayor [[Anthony_A._Williams|Anthony A. Williams]] proposed re-extending Yellow Line service to {{wmata|Fort Totten}} or even to {{wmata|Greenbelt}}, which was the originally planned northern terminus for the line. Their proposal did not involve construction of any new track, because either extension would run along the same route as the existing Green Line and would thus relieve crowding on that line. Suburban members of the board initially resisted the proposal. Through a compromise that also increased service on the [[Red_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Red Line]], on April 20, 2006 the WMATA board approved a Yellow Line extension to the Fort Totten station during off-peak hours. An 18-month pilot program began on December 31, 2006, at a cost of $5.75 million to the District of Columbia.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority |date=December 26, 2006 |url=https://www.wmata.com/about/news/pressreleasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=3973 |title=Metro Extends Yellow Line to Fort Totten During Off-Peak Hours |access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> At the end of the pilot, the program was extended<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.wmata.com/about/news/pressreleasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=2160 |title=Metro Board approves budget that includes improved rail and bus service  |publisher=WMATA |date=June 26, 2008 |access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> and as of April 2019, is operational today.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/schedules/timetables/index.cfm |title=Timetables |website=WMATA |access-date=April 25, 2019 |quote=** Yellow Line trains operate between Huntington & Mt Vernon Sq Monday through Friday from 5:00 a.m. to 10:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m. to 7:30 p.m. and between Huntington and Fort Totten from 10:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. and 7:30 p.m. to close Monday through Friday, all day Saturday and all day Sunday.}}</ref>

From March 26, 2020 until June 28, 2020, trains were bypassing {{wmata|Archives}}, {{wmata|Mount Vernon Square}}, and {{wmata|College Park–University of Maryland}} stations due to the [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington,_D.C.|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=covidmap>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/schedules/maps/upload/2019-System-Map-COVID-19-stations-FINAL.pdf |title=Special Covid-19 System Map |publisher=[[Washington_Metropolitan_Area_Transit_Authority|Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=covidservice>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/covid-station-closures.cfm |title=Metrorail stations closed due to COVID-19 pandemic |date=March 23, 2020 |publisher=[[Washington_Metropolitan_Area_Transit_Authority|Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> All stations were reopened beginning on June 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metro to reopen 15 stations, reallocate bus service to address crowding, starting Sunday {{!}} WMATA |url=https://www.wmata.com/about/news/Metro-to-reopen-15-stations-reallocate-bus-service.cfm |website=www.wmata.com |access-date=22 June 2020}}</ref>

Between May 29 to September 6, 2021, all Green Line trains terminated at {{wmata|Fort Totten}} due to the platform improvement project which closed stations north of Fort Totten. Shuttle buses were provided to the closed stations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alternative Travel Options Summer 2021 {{!}} WMATA |url=https://www.wmata.com/service/rail/PlatformProject/Alternative-Travel-Options-summer-2021.cfm |website=www.wmata.com |access-date=29 May 2021}}</ref>
{{transf}}

